      "6_8": "6–8",
      "planning_fairness_autonomy_and_natural_consequences": "Planning, fairness, autonomy, and natural consequences.",
      "checklists_timers_co_created_expectations_fewer_rewards": "Checklists, timers, co-created expectations, fewer rewards, more ownership.",
      "8_10": "8–10",
      "respect_privacy_meaningful_responsibility_and_collaborat": "Respect, privacy, meaningful responsibility, and collaborative limits.",
      "written_agreements_or_mature_checklists_avoid_childish_s": "Written agreements or mature checklists; avoid childish systems unless the child likes them.",
      "the_practical_rule_is_simple_if_the_child": "The practical rule is simple: if the child cannot do the routine, make it easier. If the child can do it but will not start, make it more visible, more playful, or more motivating. If the child can do it and starts reliably, fade support and give them more ownership.",
      "7_the_flipzy_loop_2": "7. The Flipzy Loop",
      "the_flipzy_loop_is_the_method_behind_the": "The Flipzy Loop is the method behind the handbook. It keeps routines from becoming just another command system. You use the loop whenever you introduce a routine, repair a routine, or help a child through a difficult transition.",
      "connect": "Connect",
      "briefly_enter_the_child_s_world_before_giving": "Briefly enter the child’s world before giving direction. “That tower is huge. You worked hard on it.”",
      "prepare": "Prepare",
      "say_what_is_coming_in_five_minutes_we": "Say what is coming. “In five minutes, we start bedtime.”",
      "show": "Show",
      "point_to_the_routine_or_tile_check_flipzy": "Point to the routine or tile. “Check Flipzy. First pajamas.”",
      "practice": "Practice",
      "do_the_skill_together_before_expecting_independence_i": "Do the skill together before expecting independence. “I start one sleeve, you do the other.”",
      "celebrate": "Celebrate",
      "notice_the_exact_behavior_you_started_after_one": "Notice the exact behavior. “You started after one reminder. That helped.”",
      "repair": "Repair",
      "when_it_fails_adjust_instead_of_quitting_tomorrow": "When it fails, adjust instead of quitting. “Tomorrow we make the first step smaller.”",
      "this_loop_also_protects_the_parent_from_overtalking": "This loop also protects the parent from overtalking. Many routine problems get worse because the adult keeps explaining, convincing, warning, and repeating. The child hears pressure, not clarity. The loop gives the adult a calmer path: connect briefly, show the step, help start, celebrate effort, and repair later.",
      "8_how_to_introduce_flipzy_without_turning_it": "8. How to introduce Flipzy without turning it into pressure",
      "introduce_flipzy_during_a_calm_moment_not_during": "Introduce Flipzy during a calm moment, not during the worst bedtime meltdown of the month. The first experience should feel like discovery. Put it on the table or wall, let the child touch it, flip pieces, choose stickers, and explore. If the first message is “You never listen, so now we need this,” the tool already feels like punishment.",
      "a_better_introduction_is_sometimes_mornings_feel_rushed": "A better introduction is: “Sometimes mornings feel rushed. This will help us remember what comes next.” That sentence puts the problem outside the child. The child is not the problem; the routine is the thing the family is improving together.",
      "start_with_one_routine_parents_often_want_to": "Start with one routine. Parents often want to fix morning, bedtime, screens, cleanup, meals, and chores immediately. That is too much. Choose one common routine that matters but is not the most explosive problem in the house. For many families, the best starter is not bedtime, because bedtime is already emotionally loaded. A better first routine might be coming home, getting dressed, putting shoes away, or a small cleanup sequence.",
      "for_the_first_week_reward_participation_more_than": "For the first week, reward participation more than perfection. The child is not only learning the task; they are learning the system. Notice when they check the board, when they flip a tile, when they remember one step, or when they recover after getting distracted. The first win is not a flawless routine. The first win is that the routine becomes a shared language.",
      "use_flipzy_s_modular_tiles_to_start_with": "Use Flipzy’s modular tiles to start with a small, visible routine.",
      "9_predefined_routine_library_2": "9. Predefined routine library",
      "parents_need_ready_made_starting_points_nobody_should": "Parents need ready-made starting points. Nobody should have to invent a perfect routine while the child is already upset. A predefined routine gives the family a calm first version. From there, parents can rearrange, remove, or replace steps until the sequence fits their child.",
      "the_examples_below_are_practical_starter_packs_not": "The examples below are practical starter packs, not strict rules. A family can use the same Flipzy board for morning, evening, after-school, chores, calm transitions, weekend anchors, or sibling teamwork. Choose the version that feels closest to your daily life, then make it simpler if the routine still feels too big.",
      "a_routine_system_becomes_easier_when_parents_can": "A routine system becomes easier when parents can pick from a visible task library instead of inventing every step from scratch.",
